{
  "text": "where 1, 2, and 3 \u0351or x, y, z in other parts of the paper\u0352 refer to the streamwise, cross-stream, and vertical directions, respectively. At the bottom of the domain, the vertical velocity is set to 0 at the surface. As a consequence of the staggered grid formulation, no boundary conditions are needed for the horizontal velocities since they are only stored at a distance dz / 2 above the surface. Stresses at the surface are imposed through a local similarity theory formulation [CITATION_1] \u0351see Piomelli and Balaras [CITATION_2] for a review of wall modeling in LES\u0352. However, velocities filtered at twice the grid scale are used to compute the surface stress; this is needed to ensure that the average stress over the wall is close to the stress predicted by the classic log law. The need for this formulation and its derivation are explained in the Appendix. The resulting lawof-the-wall formulation is",
